Kailua, Hawaii
February 22, 2026

Dear Grandma Ruth,

I know you would rather have a phone call, and we will have one this Sunday like
always, but some things I want to say slowly, and you can hold a letter in your hands
and read it twice. So here is a letter.

I have decided. I am coming to Atlanta. Not "when things settle down," not "when the
season ends," not "when I save a little more." I have been saying that for years and
you have been gracious about it and I am done saying it. I am planning the trip for
late January or early February of next year, 2027, which gives me time to do it right
and put a little money aside each month without it being a strain. I will fly into
Atlanta and stay the better part of a week. I am not booking a hotel. I will take your
couch and you will keep your own bed, and we are not going to argue about it.

Here is what I want from the trip, so you know and so you do not go wearing yourself
out trying to entertain me: I want to sit in your kitchen. That is most of it. I want
to drink coffee with you in the morning with nothing on the schedule, and I want you
to tell me about Atlanta in the sixties, the neighborhood before it changed, the choir,
your years at the insurance company. I have heard some of these stories and I want to
hear them again, and I want to hear the ones I have not heard yet. If you are feeling
strong one of the days, I would love to finally take you to the Georgia Aquarium. You
have mentioned it for years. And if you are not feeling up to it, we will stay in, watch
old movies, and that will be just as good a day. There is no wrong version of this trip.

I want to cook your collard greens with you. The real way, the way you taught Mom. I
have been making a pescatarian version out here (I stopped eating meat a while back,
Dad gave me a hard time and then quietly admitted it was fine) and it is good but it
is not yours. I want to stand at your stove and get it right.

One thing, and you can say no. You told me the old black-and-white photo of you in your
thirties is fading. While I am there I would like to take it to a good print shop and
have an archival copy made, so the fading one can rest and you have a clean one to keep.
I think about that photo a lot.

Work is good. The reef is actually recovering, Grandma, which after the last few years
is not a small thing to be able to write down. The corals that bleached white are
getting their color back from the edges in. I take the same photographs at the same
places year after year and I am finally photographing something coming back instead of
something going. I will bring printed pictures so you can see them clearly, the before
and the after. You always did like hearing about the fish.

Everyone here sends love. Sam is well, you would like him, he is steady and he is kind
and he does not say much, which I think you would approve of. Jenna too. Dad says he is
going to call you more and I am going to hold him to it. Marcus might fly down from
Seattle for a day while I am there, we are working on it, and wouldn't that be something,
two of us at your table at once.

You are 87 and I love you and the timing is now. I will see you soon. Keep the coffee on.

All my love,
Lorraine

P.S. I am bringing good Kona beans from home so do not buy coffee for my visit. And tell
Mrs. Coleman I said hello and thank you for keeping that spare key.
